.TH HAPTICCTL 1 "2025" "hapticctl 0.1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
hapticctl \- control haptic touchpad feedback intensity on Linux
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hapticctl
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fICOMMAND\fR [\fIARGS\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hapticctl
controls the haptic feedback intensity of precision touchpads that expose
a HID haptic intensity feature report (Usage Page 0x0E, Usage 0x23), as
defined in the Microsoft Precision Touchpad specification.

It communicates directly with the device via the kernel
.I hidraw
interface, bypassing libinput and any other higher-level input stack.

State is persisted across reboots via a plain text file under
\fI$XDG_STATE_HOME/hapticctl/intensity\fR (user mode) or
\fI/var/lib/hapticctl/intensity\fR (system mode).
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B get
Print the current intensity. Attempts a hardware read first; falls back to
the saved state if the device does not support feature report reads.
.TP
.B set \fIVALUE\fR
Set intensity to \fIVALUE\fR (0\[en]100). Saves the value for future restores.
.TP
.B up
Step up to the next preset level above the current value.
.TP
.B down
Step down to the next preset level below the current value.
.TP
.B cycle
Advance to the next preset level, wrapping from max back to off.
Useful as a keyboard shortcut action.
.TP
.B restore
Apply the last saved intensity. Intended for use by the systemd service on login.
.TP
.B status
Print a human-readable summary: device path, current intensity, and level name.
.TP
.B list-devices
Scan \fI/dev/hidraw*\fR and list devices that expose a haptic intensity feature.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-d, \-\-device \fIPATH\fR
Use \fIPATH\fR as the hidraw device instead of auto-detecting.
.TP
.B \-r, \-\-report-id \fIN\fR
HID feature report ID for haptic intensity (default: 9).
.TP
.B \-\-levels \fILEVELS\fR
Override the preset level map. Comma-separated \fIname:value\fR pairs,
e.g. \fIoff:0,low:33,high:66,max:100\fR.
.TP
.B \-n, \-\-notify
Send a desktop notification via
.BR notify-send (1)
when the intensity changes. Shows a visual level indicator.
.TP
.B \-m, \-\-machine
Machine-readable output: print only the numeric value, no level name.
.TP
.B \-\-system
Use the system-wide state file \fI/var/lib/hapticctl/intensity\fR.
Useful when running as root or from a system-level service.
.TP
.B \-\-version
Print version and exit.
.SH DEFAULT LEVELS
.TS
l l.
off	0
low	25
medium	50
high	75
max	100
.TE
.SH PERMISSIONS
.B hapticctl
requires read/write access to \fI/dev/hidrawN\fR. By default this requires root.
Install the provided udev rule to grant access to members of the \fBinput\fR group:
.PP
.RS
.nf
sudo cp contrib/70-hapticctl.rules /etc/udev/rules.d/
sudo udevadm control --reload-rules && sudo udevadm trigger
sudo usermod -aG input $USER
.fi
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Set intensity to maximum:
.B hapticctl set 100
.TP
Step up one level with a notification:
.B hapticctl --notify up
.TP
Cycle through levels (assign to a keyboard shortcut):
.B hapticctl --notify cycle
.TP
Print current intensity as a number (for scripts):
.B hapticctl --machine get
.TP
Restore saved intensity at login:
.B hapticctl restore
.TP
List detected haptic devices:
.B hapticctl list-devices
.SH FILES
.TP
.I $XDG_STATE_HOME/hapticctl/intensity
Per-user saved intensity (typically \fI~/.local/state/hapticctl/intensity\fR).
.TP
.I /var/lib/hapticctl/intensity
System-wide saved intensity (used with \fB--system\fR or when run as root).
.TP
.I /etc/udev/rules.d/70-hapticctl.rules
udev rule for non-root access.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR brightnessctl (1),
.BR udevadm (8),
.BR systemctl (1)
